In Los Angeles we were met by our old and best Chinese friends
Violet and Ki Chun.
They took us to the Statler Hilton where they had
made reservations for us and that night we had
Chinese chow at their son-
"Doc" Wong's restaurant in Chinatown.
We really should not have
gone because 7 p.m. their time was 3 a.m. for us but we couldn't say
We were with them almost all the time during the next two days.
all over Los Angeles and among other things took in the Huntington Library
which neither of us had seen before.
Debby took one morning off to see Jane Gordon.
The evening of Monday the 4th we went to Gordon Chun's home for
drinks followed by
Chinese chow at a nearby restaurant.
Florence and
"Alli"
Allison, old China hands, were there too and we had a lot of fun.
The next morning, Tuesday, November 5th,
the Chuns with their
daughter, Mrs.
who was with us practically all the time, despite
three boys and a daughter to look after at home, called for us at the hotel
and took us to the airport.
and climbed up to 35,000 feet.
Our flight forecast was 4:55 (which we hit right on the nose.)
back to the first flight which I made back in 1936 when it took us almost
24 hours to make the run from San Francisco to Honolulu.
When we got on
the ground I also thought back to my first visit here in 1909.
it we took a two horse-drawn conveyance with three seats to hold the driver
and eight passengers along a dirt road from Honolulu to Waikiki beach.
Today there is just one big apartment building after another all along the
beach and back away from it too.
The only thing that hasn't changed is the
weather, the soft
gentle air such as exists no where else in the world and
which you can always bank on.
We have
decided to leave here on Sunday, November 17th to fly to
Pago Pago in American Samoa from where we will go to British Samoa close
by for a few days and then fly to Fiji which will probably be the best
place to

Last night we had dinner with the Mullaheys at their apartment
at the Diamond Head end of
Waikiki beach.
They have a magnificent view
of the whole circular harbor.
Dr. and Mrs. Dana Nance and Dr. and Mrs.
Frick Nance were there too.
They are old China hands, members of a
Missionary family born in China.

It was a great pleasure to see them
They are both practicing in Honolulu and doing well.
